{'highlightedComments': ['Thanks for a fascinating conversation!'], 'highlightedCommentsActivityCounts': [{'text': 'Thanks for a fascinating conversation!', 'totalReactionCount': 26, 'likeCount': 23, 'empathyCount': 2, 'praiseCount': 1}], 'text': 'Hey folks, We have a pretty exciting guest on the Next Big Idea podcast this week — Bill Gates.

The topic? Artificial Intelligence, and how it will change our world. 

Here's a small sampling of the points Bill makes in this conversation:

- Superhuman AI is coming. 
- There is no clear way to slow it down. 
- The technology available today is *already* a game changer. 
- We will all soon have intelligent agents that function as "executive assistants, mental therapists, and friends."
- AI has the potential to help us solve the most intractable global problems, it has the potential to help us all get along better, and it's likely to deliver us to a world of superabundance. But it also poses "novel" threats, given the pace of it's acceleration and the lack of "clear upper bound" of it's capability. 

Listen on Apple or Spotify ... I look forward to discussing with you in the comments below!

https://lnkd.in/enx2qmNU

https://lnkd.in/e9cPaxtG

Looking forward to continuing our work together in the years ahead.\xa0', 'totalReactionCount': 20, 'likeCount': 18, 'empathyCount': 2}], 'resharedPost': {'text': 'I am pleased to announce the appointment of Dr. Paulin BASINGA as the new director, Africa at the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation.\xa0 

Paulin is a 12-year veteran of the foundation and brings extensive experience and insights into building and strengthening partnerships across Africa. He’ll be based in Nairobi, Kenya when the foundation’s office opens there. 

Over the course of his tenure at the foundation, he led strategic initiatives across our programmatic and country priorities, advanced policy and advocacy objectives in support of the foundation’s health, development, and gender equality goals, previously led the foundation’s Nigeria Country Office, and served as director, Health for our work in Africa. 

Paulin is a dynamic leader and trusted partner of country governments, donors, and grantees. I look forward to Paulin leading the Africa team as we work in partnership with many others to advance ambitious health and development goals in Africa.', 'author': {'firstName': 'Chris', 'lastName': 'Elias', 'username': 'chris-elias-3971605', 'url': 'https://www.linkedin.com/in/chris-elias-3971605'}, 'image': [{'url': 'https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D5622AQF4NVs23nF_Tw/feedshare-shrink_2048_1536/feedshare-shrink_2048_1536/0/1709298019594?e=1733961600&v=beta&t=b3SYN5CClQOAIT3TeJz9w8CQzMGfQD2DQjSRZp2pfG8'}], 'company': {}, 'document': {}, 'celebration': {}, 'poll': {}, 'article': {}, 'entity': {}}, 'text': "I'm thrilled to embark on a new chapter as the Africa Director at the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation. 

For 12 years, I’ve been privileged to contribute to health and development initiatives, working alongside our inspiring partners to tackle the world’s most pressing development challenges.

Now, I’m honored to take on a new challenge leading our remarkable teams in Africa. I’m committed to finding innovative solutions to improve health outcomes, promote gender equality and financial inclusion, and build climate resilience and sustainable development. 

Together with our partners and many governments we work with, we’ll champion innovative solutions, drive real progress, and advance the foundation’s mission of creating a world where everyone has the opportunity to live a healthy, productive life.

I can't wait to read this book—and for all your readers to learn just how contagious\xa0kindness can be.​"], 'highlightedCommentsActivityCounts': [{'text': "Congratulations, Chris. I can't wait to read this book—and for all your readers to learn just how contagious\xa0kindness can be.​", 'totalReactionCount': 150, 'likeCount': 131, 'appreciationCount': 2, 'empathyCount': 11, 'InterestCount': 4, 'praiseCount': 2}], 'text': "I'm so happy that after a three-year labor of love this is book is finally published. It argues that the combination of new findings in psychology and the incredible connectedness of the modern world create a new way to think about generosity. One that just might help turn the tide on today's mean, cynical, angry, divided culture.  Seems daunting... Maybe crazy...  But if kindness can go viral, all bets are off.  

I truly believe that any forward-leaning company can benefit from brainstorming its own generosity strategy.  And yes, I use the word strategy very deliberately. 

I really hope some of you will get a chance to read this. And I would be fascinated to hear what you make of it.  You can find links to the seller of your choice at https://lnkd.in/edg6JzZM  
(also a link to our delightful new generosity AI!)

P.S. {'highlightedComments': ['This is great.'], 'highlightedCommentsActivityCounts': [{'text': 'This is great.', 'totalReactionCount': 19, 'likeCount': 16, 'appreciationCount': 2, 'empathyCount': 1}], 'text': 'This shook me - in the best possible way. 

The wonderful behavioural scientists and psychologists at BEworks just launched a report here at #cop28 on personality traits, mindsets and climate change. 

One discovery they made - a shockingly strong correlation between creativity  and climate optimism! Basically, the more creative your personality then the more likely you are to see solutions and answers to the climate crisis.

I guess I shouldn’t be surprised. For my book The Solutionists I found much higher levels of climate optimism amoungst folks actually working on answers. But it’s stark to see the psychological correlation laid out like this. Inventiveness, lateral thinking, imagination - creative traits that can see a way through the fuggy mess we’re in.

Futerra has been bringing creativity and storytelling here to #cop28uae - but after the dust settles we’ll continue bringing climate to the entertainment industry, social media and the culture sector. Because we must recruit the creatives into climate action. If we want a better future, we need to imagine it first! 

On second thoughts, maybe I’m not that shocked by this research after all 😉

So I've set myself a goal to take the extra time to connect with colleagues and partners, to listen to their experiences and ask them, and myself, the tough questions. I am especially excited to spend my first week as CEO in South Africa, where I was raised and where exposure to apartheid first instilled in me a desire to use the advantages afforded to me to help tackle injustice and inequality.
